\begin_layout Subsubsection
Some behind the scenes choices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function has a number of behind the scenes choices that have been made
 based on my experience.
 These include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Parameter restrictions
\series default
: The estimation routine used, 
\family typewriter
fminunc
\family default
, is unconstrained but this is deceptive.
 The parameters are constrained to satisfy: 
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1,2,\ldots P$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}+\gamma_{o}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1,2,\ldots P$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $o=1,2,\ldots O$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{q}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1,2,\ldots Q$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{p=1}^{P}\alpha+0.5\sum_{o=1}^{O}\gamma+\sum_{q=1}^{Q}\beta<1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>2.1$
\end_inset

 for a Student's 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 or Skew 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>1.05$
\end_inset

 for a GED 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $-.995<\lambda<.995$
\end_inset

 for a Skew 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Some of these are necessary but the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{q}>0$
\end_inset

 is not when 
\begin_inset Formula $Q>1$
\end_inset

.
 This may lead to issues in estimating models with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q>1$
\end_inset

 and the function will return constrained QML estimates.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Starting Values
\series default
: The starting values are computed using a grid of reasonable values (experience
 driven).
 The log-likelihood is evaluated on this grid and the best fit is used to
 start.
 If the optimizer fails to converge, other starting values will be tried
 to see of a convergent LL can be found.
 This said, 
\family typewriter
tarch
\family default
 will never return parameter estimates from anything but the largest LL.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Back Casts
\series default
: Back casts are computed using a local algorithm using 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 data points, 
\begin_inset Formula $backcast=\sum_{i=1}^{\lfloor T^{1/2}\rfloor}w_{i}|r_{i}|^{\delta}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is 1 or 2 depending on the model specification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Covariance Estimates
\series default
: The covariance estimated are produces using 2-sided numerical scores and
 Hessian.
 
\end_layout

